            "text": "where",
            "type": "header-three",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "c85hp",
            "text": "Additional annotations may appear in brackets as follows:",
            "type": "header-three",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "gtds",
            "text": "Strain ID",
            "type": "header-two",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "4dcfg",
            "text":
                "All strains curated by dictyBase also have a strain ID consisting of the letters DBS (dictyBase Strain) followed by seven digits. This ID is created automatically and does not change. If there is no other Systematic Strain Name, both the Strain ID and the Systematic Strain Name will be the same.",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 86, "length": 1, "style": "BOLD" },
                { "offset": 91, "length": 1, "style": "BOLD" },
                { "offset": 96, "length": 1, "style": "BOLD" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "23csj",
            "text": "[TOP]",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [{ "offset": 0, "length": 5, "key": 20 }],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "bejn4",
            "text": "Phenotypes",
            "type": "header-two",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "8ud15",
            "text":
                "dictyBase is using a vocabulary based on PATO (Phenotypic Quality Ontology) for phenotype annotations. Some documentation is available at http://www.bioontology.org/wiki/index.php/PATO:Main_Page. Phenotype terms are composed of two terms: an entity (biological process or anatomical structure abnormal in the mutant) and a quality that describes the abnormality. For example, a mutant that exhibits a delay in the aggregation process will be annotated to \"delayed aggregation.\" The complete list of terms used to annotate Dictyostelium phenotypes can be viewed here: http://dictybase.org/Downloads/dicty_phenotypes.html. We encourage researchers to use this vocabulary in publications to ensure that genes get annotated accurately.",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 242, "length": 6, "style": "BOLD" },
                { "offset": 323, "length": 7, "style": "BOLD" },
                { "offset": 522, "length": 13, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [
                { "offset": 138, "length": 56, "key": 21 },
                { "offset": 567, "length": 52, "key": 22 }
            ],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "9qnme",
            "text": "[TOP]",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [{ "offset": 0, "length": 5, "key": 23 }],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "79tq0",
            "text": "Genotypes",
            "type": "header-two",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "3v1ll",
            "text":
                "Genotypes represent the genetic modifications present in a given strain. Genes listed in a genotype are considered to be mutant in some way. Every genetic element described in a genotype (gene, plasmid, DNA fragment) should be separated by a comma. To distinguish chromosomal loci from exogenous genes, every gene or construct contained on DNA that was introduced into cells by transformation should be listed within brackets regardless of whether that DNA is carried on a plasmid, integrated as a fragment or was amplified by replication once inside cells.",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [{ "offset": 473, "length": 7, "key": 24 }],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "5udq0",
            "text":
                "Constructs carried within cells should be described in the formal genotype of that strain and placed in brackets. Thus, a cotB promoter beta-galactosidase reporter construct in a mutant strain might have a formal genotype of “regA(AK202), [cotB/lacZ], neoR”, but could be shortened to “regA-[cotB/lacZ]” in the context of a sentence describing the strain's properties in the results section of a paper.\n\nThe following names should be used to indicate common drug resistance/sensitivity and nutrient auxotrophy/prototrophy. For clarity, relevant phenotypic markers should be included at the end of formal genotypes (no italics):",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 122, "length": 4, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 226, "length": 10, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 240, "length": 9, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 286, "length": 4, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 292, "length": 9, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "3gnb1",
            "text": "Drug resistance:",
            "type": "header-three",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "dat62",
            "text": "bleR: bleomycin resistance",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "5tman",
            "text":
                "bsR: indicates the blasticidin resistance gene bsr is present",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 47, "length": 3, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "bq29g",
            "text":
                "bsS: for clarity, or when bsr has been introduced but is non-functional",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 26, "length": 3, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "egmh",
            "text": "foaR: most often this will be redundant with ura-",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 45, "length": 4, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "ca3q3",
            "text": "hygR: hygromycin resistance",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "5cur2",
            "text":
                "neoR: indicates a neomycin phosphotransferase gene is functional",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "1r7kj",
            "text":
                "neoS: for clarity, or when G418 selection on a neoR strain is relaxed and G418-sensitive strain is isolated\n\n",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "ama46",
            "text": "Auxotrophic markers:",
            "type": "header-three",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "a98r4",
            "text":
                "thy-: indicates thy1 is mutant and the strain requires thymidine",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 16, "length": 4, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "95uee",
            "text": "thy+: used when a thy1 mutant has been complemented",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 18, "length": 4, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "71p4t",
            "text":
                "ura+: uracil independent Note that this can be different from pyr5-6+",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 62, "length": 7, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "bbi3q",
            "text": "ura-: most often used to indicate pyr5-6-",
            "type": "unordered-list-item",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 34, "length": 7, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "94dbi",
            "text": "[TOP]",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [{ "offset": 0, "length": 5, "key": 25 }],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "augs8",
            "text": "Plasmids",
            "type": "header-two",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "q6k7",
            "text":
                "Naturally occurring plasmids are named by a prefix indicating the genus and species, as in Ddp1. Derivatives of the natural plasmids and other shuttle vectors should be indicated with a lowercase “p” prefix (pDXA-3C). For genes on a plasmid, and any other gene that is introduced into a strain by experiment (see below), use the same naming system as for chromosomal genes, but placed within square brackets.\nExample: pDneo67[act6/regA] indicates that the regA coding sequence is fused to the promoter of the actin6 gene on plasmid pDneo67).",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 426, "length": 9, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 456, "length": 4, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 509, "length": 6, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "lph4",
            "text": "[TOP]",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [{ "offset": 0, "length": 5, "key": 26 }],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "59kgf",
            "text": "Molecular Genetic Constructs",
            "type": "header-two",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
        {
            "key": "bhh46",
            "text":
                "Reporter genes and gene fusions should be named with the relevant components separated by slashes and dashes to indicate DNA fusion, as follows. Typically, the components will be a promoter, a coding sequence or ORF encoding a reporter protein. Promoters (± a few codons) should be separated from coding sequence by a slash (/) and coding sequences separated by dashes (-).\nExamples: cotB/talA-GFP (talin-GFP fusion under the transcriptional control of the cotB promoter), talA/talA-GFP or talA-GFP (talin gene under the transcriptional control of the native promoter), talA-GFP(S65T).",
            "type": "unstyled",
            "depth": 0,
            "inlineStyleRanges": [
                { "offset": 384, "length": 13, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 457, "length": 4, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 473, "length": 13, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 490, "length": 8, "style": "ITALIC" },
                { "offset": 570, "length": 8, "style": "ITALIC" }
            ],
            "entityRanges": [],
            "data": {}
        },
